ion rate and produces a different dependence on mass, both of which are observed. The derived Z(m star, SFR) relation for the regulator system is fit to published Z(m star, SFR) data for the SDSS galaxy population, yielding …õ and Œª as functions of m star. The fitted …õ is consistent with observed molecular gas-depletion timescales in galaxies (allowing for the extra atomic gas), while the fitted Œª is also reasonable. The gas-regulator model also successfully reproduces the Z(m star) metallicities of star-forming galaxies at z {\textasciitilde} 2. One consequence of this analysis is that it suggests that the m star-m halo relation is established by baryonic processes operating within galaxies, and that a significant fraction (40\%) of baryons coming into the halos are being processed through the galaxies. This fraction may be more or less constant. The success of the gas-regulator model in simultaneously explaining many diverse observed relations over the 0 {\textless} z {\textless} 2 interval suggests that the evolution of galaxies is governed by simple physics that form the basis for this model.},
